# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: text-generation-inference
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:text-generation-inference/application-checkpointing] In the distributed computing environment, checkpointing is a technique that helps tolerate failures that would otherwise force a long-running application to restart from the beginning.
[src:text-generation-inference/application-checkpointing] The most basic way to implement checkpointing is to stop the application, copy all the required data from the memory to reliable storage (e.g., parallel file system), then continue with execution.
[src:text-generation-inference/application-checkpointing] In the case of failure, when the application restarts, it does not need to start from scratch.
[src:text-generation-inference/application-checkpointing] Rather, it will read the latest state ("the checkpoint") from the stable storage and execute from that point.
[src:text-generation-inference/application-checkpointing] While there is ongoing debate on whether checkpointing is the dominant I/O workload on distributed computing systems, the general consensus is that checkpointing is one of the major I/O workloads.
[src:text-generation-inference/application-checkpointing] There are two main approaches for checkpointing in the distributed computing systems: coordinated checkpointing and uncoordinated checkpointing.
[src:text-generation-inference/application-checkpointing] In the coordinated checkpointing approach, processes must ensure that their checkpoints are consistent.
[src:text-generation-inference/application-checkpointing] This is usually achieved by some kind of two-phase commit protocol algorithm.
[src:text-generation-inference/application-checkpointing] In the uncoordinated checkpointing, each process checkpoints its own state independently.
[src:text-generation-inference/application-checkpointing] It must be stressed that simply forcing processes to checkpoint their state at fixed time intervals is not sufficient to ensure global consistency.
[src:text-generation-inference/application-checkpointing] This was implemented through a "save" command or menu option in the application.
[src:text-generation-inference/application-checkpointing] In many cases, it became standard practice to ask the user, if they had unsaved work when exiting an application, if they wanted to save their work before doing so.
[src:text-generation-inference/application-checkpointing] The problem with save state is it requires the operator of a program to request the save.
[src:text-generation-inference/application-checkpointing] For non-interactive programs, including automated or batch processed workloads, the ability to checkpoint such applications also had to be automated.
[src:text-generation-inference/application-checkpointing] Thus the "checkpoint/restart" capability was born, in which after a number of transactions had been processed, a "snapshot" or "checkpoint" of the state of the application could be taken.
[src:text-generation-inference/application-checkpointing] If the application failed before the next checkpoint, it could be restarted by giving it the checkpoint information and the last place in the transaction file where a transaction had successfully completed.
[src:text-generation-inference/application-checkpointing] The application could then restart at that point.
[src:text-generation-inference/application-checkpointing] Checkpointing tends to be expensive, so it was generally not done with every record, but at some reasonable compromise between the cost of a checkpoint vs. the value of the computer time needed to reprocess a batch of records.
[src:text-generation-inference/application-checkpointing] Thus the number of records processed for each checkpoint might range from 25 to 200, depending on cost factors, the relative complexity of the application and the resources needed to successfully restart the application.
[src:text-generation-inference/application-checkpointing] FTI is a library that aims to provide computational scientists with an easy way to perform checkpoint/restart in a scalable fashion.
[src:text-generation-inference/application-checkpointing] FTI leverages local storage plus multiple replications and erasures techniques to provide several levels of reliability and performance.
[src:text-generation-inference/application-checkpointing] FTI provides application-level checkpointing that allows users to select which data needs to be protected, in order to improve efficiency and avoid space, time and energy waste.
[src:text-generation-inference/application-checkpointing] It offers a direct data interface so that users do not need to deal with files and/or directory names.
[src:text-generation-inference/application-checkpointing] All metadata is managed by FTI in a transparent fashion for the user.
[src:text-generation-inference/application-checkpointing] If desired, users can dedicate one process per node to overlap fault tolerance workload and scientific computation, so that post-checkpoint tasks are executed asynchronously.
[src:text-generation-inference/application-checkpointing] The Future Technologies Group at the Lawrence National Laboratories are developing a hybrid kernel/user implementation of checkpoint/restart called BLCR.
[src:text-generation-inference/application-checkpointing] Their goal is to provide a robust, production quality implementation that checkpoints a wide range of applications, without requiring changes to be made to application code.
[src:text-generation-inference/application-checkpointing] BLCR focuses on checkpointing parallel applications that communicate through MPI, and on compatibility with the software suite produced by the SciDAC Scalable Systems Software ISIC.
[src:text-generation-inference/application-checkpointing] Its work is broken down into 4 main areas: Checkpoint/Restart for Linux (CR), Checkpointable MPI Libraries, Resource Management Interface to Checkpoint/Restart and Development of Process Management Interfaces.
[src:text-generation-inference/application-checkpointing] DMTCP (Distributed MultiThreaded Checkpointing) is a tool for transparently checkpointing the state of an arbitrary group of programs spread across many machines and connected by sockets.
[src:text-generation-inference/application-checkpointing] It does not modify the user's program or the operating system.
[src:text-generation-inference/application-checkpointing] Among the applications supported by DMTCP are Open MPI, Python, Perl, and many programming languages and shell scripting languages.
[src:text-generation-inference/application-checkpointing] With the use of TightVNC, it can also checkpoint and restart X Window applications, as long as they do not use extensions (e.g. no OpenGL or video).
[src:text-generation-inference/application-checkpointing] DMTCP supports the OFED API for InfiniBand on an experimental basis.
[src:text-generation-inference/application-checkpointing] Some recent protocols perform collaborative checkpointing by storing fragments of the checkpoint in nearby nodes.
[src:text-generation-inference/application-checkpointing] This is helpful because it avoids the cost of storing to a parallel file system (which often becomes a bottleneck for large-scale systems) and it uses storage that is closer.
[src:text-generation-inference/application-checkpointing] This has found use particularly in large-scale supercomputing clusters.
[src:text-generation-inference/application-checkpointing] The challenge is to ensure that when the checkpoint is needed when recovering from a failure, the nearby nodes with fragments of the checkpoints are available.
[src:text-generation-inference/application-checkpointing] Docker and the underlying technology contain a checkpoint and restore mechanism.
[src:text-generation-inference/application-checkpointing] CRIU is a user space checkpoint library.
[src:text-generation-inference/application-checkpointing] Mementos is a software system that transforms general-purpose tasks into interruptible programs for platforms with frequent interruptions such as power outages.
[src:text-generation-inference/application-checkpointing] It was designed for batteryless embedded devices such as RFID tags and smart cards which rely on harvesting energy from ambient background sources.
[src:text-generation-inference/application-checkpointing] Mementos frequently senses the available energy in the system and decides whether to checkpoint the program due to impending power loss versus continuing computation.
[src:text-generation-inference/application-checkpointing] If checkpointing, data will be stored in a non-volatile memory.
[src:text-generation-inference/application-checkpointing] When the energy becomes sufficient for reboot, the data is retrieved from non-volatile memory and the program continues from the stored state.
[src:text-generation-inference/application-checkpointing] Mementos has been implemented on the MSP430 family of microcontrollers.
[src:text-generation-inference/application-checkpointing] Idetic is a set of automatic tools which helps application-specific integrated circuit (ASIC) developers automatically embed checkpoints in their designs.
[src:text-generation-inference/application-checkpointing] It targets high-level synthesis tools and adds the checkpoints at the register-transfer level (Verilog code).
[src:text-generation-inference/application-checkpointing] It uses a dynamic programming approach to locate low overhead points in the state machine of the design.
[src:text-generation-inference/application-checkpointing] Since the checkpointing in hardware level involves sending the data of dependent registers to a non-volatile memory, the optimum points are required to have minimum number of registers to store.
[src:text-generation-inference/application-checkpointing] Idetic is deployed and evaluated on energy harvesting RFID tag device.
[src:text-generation-inference/inference-engine] In the field of artificial intelligence, an **inference engine** is a software component of an intelligent system that applies logical rules to the knowledge base to deduce new information.
[src:text-generation-inference/inference-engine] The first inference engines were components of expert systems.
[src:text-generation-inference/inference-engine] The typical expert system consisted of a knowledge base and an inference engine.
[src:text-generation-inference/inference-engine] The knowledge base stored facts about the world.
[src:text-generation-inference/inference-engine] The inference engine applied logical rules to the knowledge base and deduced new knowledge.
[src:text-generation-inference/inference-engine] This process would iterate as each new fact in the knowledge base could trigger additional rules in the inference engine.
[src:text-generation-inference/inference-engine] Inference engines work primarily in one of two modes either special rule or facts: forward chaining and backward chaining.
[src:text-generation-inference/inference-engine] Forward chaining starts with the known facts and asserts new facts.
[src:text-generation-inference/inference-engine] Backward chaining starts with goals, and works backward to determine what facts must be asserted so that the goals can be achieved.
[src:text-generation-inference/inference-engine] Additionally, the concept of 'inference' has expanded to include the process through which trained neural networks generate predictions or decisions.
[src:text-generation-inference/inference-engine] In this context, an 'inference engine' could refer to the specific part of the system, or even the hardware, that executes these operations.
[src:text-generation-inference/inference-engine] This type of inference plays a crucial role in various applications, including (but not limited to) image recognition, natural language processing, and autonomous vehicles.
[src:text-generation-inference/inference-engine] The inference phase in these applications is typically characterized by a high volume of data inputs and real-time processing requirements.
[src:text-generation-inference/inference-engine] The logic that an inference engine uses is typically represented as IF-THEN rules.
[src:text-generation-inference/inference-engine] The general format of such rules is IF <logical expression> THEN <logical expression>.
[src:text-generation-inference/inference-engine] Prior to the development of expert systems and inference engines, artificial intelligence researchers focused on more powerful theorem prover environments that offered much fuller implementations of first-order logic.
[src:text-generation-inference/inference-engine] For example, general statements that included universal quantification (for all X some statement is true) and existential quantification (there exists some X such that some statement is true).
[src:text-generation-inference/inference-engine] What researchers discovered is that the power of these theorem-proving environments was also their drawback.
[src:text-generation-inference/inference-engine] Back in 1965, it was far too easy to create logical expressions that could take an indeterminate or even infinite time to terminate.
[src:text-generation-inference/inference-engine] For example, it is common in universal quantification to make statements over an infinite set such as the set of all natural numbers.
[src:text-generation-inference/inference-engine] Such statements are perfectly reasonable and even required in mathematical proofs but when included in an automated theorem prover executing on a computer may cause the computer to fall into an infinite loop.
[src:text-generation-inference/inference-engine] Focusing on IF-THEN statements (what logicians call *modus ponens*) still gave developers a very powerful general mechanism to represent logic, but one that could be used efficiently with computational resources.
[src:text-generation-inference/inference-engine] What is more, there is some psychological research that indicates humans also tend to favor IF-THEN representations when storing complex knowledge.
[src:text-generation-inference/inference-engine] A simple example of *modus ponens* often used in introductory logic books is "If you are human then you are mortal".
[src:text-generation-inference/inference-engine] A trivial example of how this rule would be used in an inference engine is as follows.
[src:text-generation-inference/inference-engine] In *forward chaining*, the inference engine would find any facts in the knowledge base that matched Human(x) and for each fact it found would add the new information Mortal(x) to the knowledge base.
[src:text-generation-inference/inference-engine] So if it found an object called Socrates that was human it would deduce that Socrates was mortal.
[src:text-generation-inference/inference-engine] In *backward chaining*, the system would be given a goal, e.g. answer the question is Socrates mortal?
[src:text-generation-inference/inference-engine] It would search through the knowledge base and determine if Socrates was human and, if so, would assert he is also mortal.
[src:text-generation-inference/inference-engine] However, in backward chaining a common technique was to integrate the inference engine with a user interface.
[src:text-generation-inference/inference-engine] In that way, rather than simply being automated the system could now be interactive.
[src:text-generation-inference/inference-engine] In this trivial example, if the system was given the goal to answer the question if Socrates was mortal and it didn't yet know if he was human, it would generate a window to ask the user the question "Is Socrates human?" and would then use that information accordingly.
[src:text-generation-inference/inference-engine] This innovation of integrating the inference engine with a user interface led to the second early advancement of expert systems: explanation capabilities.
[src:text-generation-inference/inference-engine] The explicit representation of knowledge as rules rather than code made it possible to generate explanations to users: both explanations in real time and after the fact.
[src:text-generation-inference/inference-engine] At first these explanations were not much different than the standard debugging information that developers deal with when debugging any system.
[src:text-generation-inference/inference-engine] However, an active area of research was utilizing natural language technology to ask, understand, and generate questions and explanations using natural languages rather than computer formalisms.
[src:text-generation-inference/inference-engine] An inference engine cycles through three sequential steps: *match rules*, *select rules*, and *execute rules*.
[src:text-generation-inference/inference-engine] The execution of the rules will often result in new facts or goals being added to the knowledge base, which will trigger the cycle to repeat.
[src:text-generation-inference/inference-engine] This cycle continues until no new rules can be matched.
[src:text-generation-inference/inference-engine] In the first step, *match rules*, the inference engine finds all of the rules that are triggered by the current contents of the knowledge base.
[src:text-generation-inference/inference-engine] In forward chaining, the engine looks for rules where the antecedent (left hand side) matches some fact in the knowledge base.
[src:text-generation-inference/inference-engine] In backward chaining, the engine looks for antecedents that can satisfy one of the current goals.
[src:text-generation-inference/inference-engine] In the second step, *select rules*, the inference engine prioritizes the various rules that were matched to determine the order to execute them.
[src:text-generation-inference/inference-engine] In the final step, *execute rules*, the engine executes each matched rule in the order determined in step two and then iterates back to step one again.
[src:text-generation-inference/inference-engine] The cycle continues until no new rules are matched.
[src:text-generation-inference/inference-engine] Early inference engines focused primarily on forward chaining.
[src:text-generation-inference/inference-engine] These systems were usually implemented in the Lisp programming language.
[src:text-generation-inference/inference-engine] Lisp was a frequent platform for early AI research due to its strong capability to do symbolic manipulation.
[src:text-generation-inference/inference-engine] Also, as an interpreted language it offered productive development environments appropriate to debugging complex programs.
[src:text-generation-inference/inference-engine] A necessary consequence of these benefits was that Lisp programs tended to be slower and less robust than compiled languages of the time such as C.
[src:text-generation-inference/inference-engine] A common approach in these early days was to take an expert system application and repackage the inference engine used for that system as a re-usable tool other researchers could use for the development of other expert systems.
[src:text-generation-inference/inference-engine] For example, MYCIN was an early expert system for medical diagnosis and EMYCIN was an inference engine extrapolated from MYCIN and made available for other researchers.
[src:text-generation-inference/inference-engine] As expert systems moved from research prototypes to deployed systems there was more focus on issues such as speed and robustness.
[src:text-generation-inference/inference-engine] One of the first and most popular forward chaining engines was OPS5, which used the Rete algorithm to optimize the efficiency of rule firing.
[src:text-generation-inference/inference-engine] Another very popular technology that was developed was the Prolog logic programming language.
[src:text-generation-inference/inference-engine] Prolog focused primarily on backward chaining and also featured various commercial versions and optimizations for efficiency and robustness.
[src:text-generation-inference/inference-engine] As expert systems prompted significant interest from the business world, various companies, many of them started or guided by prominent AI researchers created productized versions of inference engines.
[src:text-generation-inference/inference-engine] For example, Intellicorp was initially guided by Edward Feigenbaum.
[src:text-generation-inference/inference-engine] These inference engine products were also often developed in Lisp at first.
[src:text-generation-inference/inference-engine] However, demands for more affordable and commercially viable platforms eventually made personal computer platforms very popular.
[src:text-generation-inference/inference-engine] ClipsRules and RefPerSys (inspired by CAIA and the work of Jacques Pitrat).
[src:text-generation-inference/inference-engine] The Frama-C static source code analyzer also uses some inference engine techniques.
[src:text-generation-inference/latency-engineering] Latency is physically a consequence of the limited velocity at which any physical interaction can propagate.
[src:text-generation-inference/latency-engineering] The magnitude of this velocity is always less than or equal to the speed of light.
[src:text-generation-inference/latency-engineering] Therefore, every physical system with any physical separation (distance) between cause and effect will experience some sort of latency, regardless of the nature of the stimulation to which it has been exposed.
[src:text-generation-inference/latency-engineering] The precise definition of latency depends on the system being observed or the nature of the simulation.
[src:text-generation-inference/latency-engineering] In communications, the lower limit of latency is determined by the medium being used to transfer information.
[src:text-generation-inference/latency-engineering] In reliable two-way communication systems, latency limits the maximum rate at which information can be transmitted, as there is often a limit on the amount of information that is in-flight at any given moment.
[src:text-generation-inference/latency-engineering] Perceptible latency has a strong effect on user satisfaction and usability in the field of human–machine interaction.
[src:text-generation-inference/latency-engineering] Online games are sensitive to latency (lag), since fast response times to new events occurring during a game session are rewarded while slow response times may carry penalties.
[src:text-generation-inference/latency-engineering] Due to a delay in transmission of game events, a player with a high-latency internet connection may show slow responses in spite of appropriate reaction time.
[src:text-generation-inference/latency-engineering] This gives players with low-latency connections a technical advantage.
[src:text-generation-inference/latency-engineering] Trading using computers has developed to the point where millisecond improvements in network speeds offer a competitive advantage for financial institutions.
[src:text-generation-inference/latency-engineering] However, in a non-trivial network, a typical packet will be forwarded over multiple links and gateways, each of which will not begin to forward the packet until it has been completely received.
[src:text-generation-inference/latency-engineering] In such a network, the minimal latency is the sum of the transmission delay of each link, plus the forwarding latency of each gateway.
[src:text-generation-inference/latency-engineering] In practice, minimal latency also includes queuing and processing delays.
[src:text-generation-inference/latency-engineering] Queuing delay occurs when a gateway receives multiple packets from different sources heading toward the same destination.
[src:text-generation-inference/latency-engineering] Since typically only one packet can be transmitted at a time, some of the packets must queue for transmission, incurring additional delay.
[src:text-generation-inference/latency-engineering] Processing delays are incurred while a gateway determines what to do with a newly received packet.
[src:text-generation-inference/latency-engineering] Bufferbloat can also cause increased latency that is an order of magnitude or more.
[src:text-generation-inference/latency-engineering] The combination of propagation, serialization, queuing, and processing delays often produces a complex and variable network latency profile.
[src:text-generation-inference/latency-engineering] Latency limits total throughput in reliable two-way communication systems as described by the bandwidth-delay product.
[src:text-generation-inference/latency-engineering] Latency in optical fiber is largely a function of the speed of light.
[src:text-generation-inference/latency-engineering] This would equate to a latency of 3.33 μs for every kilometer of path length.
[src:text-generation-inference/latency-engineering] The index of refraction of most fiber optic cables is about 1.5, meaning that light travels about 1.5 times as fast in a vacuum as it does in the cable.
[src:text-generation-inference/latency-engineering] This works out to about 5.0 μs of latency for every kilometer.
[src:text-generation-inference/latency-engineering] In shorter metro networks, higher latency can be experienced due to extra distance in building risers and cross-connects.
[src:text-generation-inference/latency-engineering] To calculate the latency of a connection, one has to know the distance traveled by the fiber, which is rarely a straight line, since it has to traverse geographic contours and obstacles, such as roads and railway tracks, as well as other rights-of-way.
[src:text-generation-inference/latency-engineering] Due to imperfections in the fiber, light degrades as it is transmitted through it.
[src:text-generation-inference/latency-engineering] For distances of greater than 100 kilometers, amplifiers or regenerators are deployed.
[src:text-generation-inference/latency-engineering] Latency introduced by these components needs to be taken into account.
[src:text-generation-inference/latency-engineering] Low Earth orbit is sometimes used to cut this delay, at the expense of more complicated satellite tracking on the ground and requiring more satellites in the satellite constellation to ensure continuous coverage.
[src:text-generation-inference/latency-engineering] Audio latency is the delay between when an audio signal enters and when it emerges from a system.
[src:text-generation-inference/latency-engineering] Potential contributors to latency in an audio system include analog-to-digital conversion, buffering, digital signal processing, transmission time, digital-to-analog conversion and the speed of sound in air.
[src:text-generation-inference/latency-engineering] Video latency refers to the degree of delay between the time a transfer of a video stream is requested and the actual time that transfer begins.
[src:text-generation-inference/latency-engineering] Networks that exhibit relatively small delays are known as low-latency networks, while their counterparts are known as high-latency networks.
[src:text-generation-inference/latency-engineering] Any individual workflow within a system of workflows can be subject to some type of operational latency.
[src:text-generation-inference/latency-engineering] It may even be the case that an individual system may have more than one type of latency, depending on the type of participant or goal-seeking behavior.
[src:text-generation-inference/latency-engineering] This is best illustrated by the following two examples involving air travel.
[src:text-generation-inference/latency-engineering] From the point of view of a passenger, latency can be described as follows.
[src:text-generation-inference/latency-engineering] Suppose John Doe flies from London to New York.
[src:text-generation-inference/latency-engineering] The latency of his trip is the time it takes him to go from his house in England to the hotel he is staying at in New York.
[src:text-generation-inference/latency-engineering] This is independent of the throughput of the London-New York air link, whether there were 100 passengers a day making the trip or 10000, the latency of the trip would remain the same.
[src:text-generation-inference/latency-engineering] From the point of view of flight operations personnel, latency can be entirely different.
[src:text-generation-inference/latency-engineering] Consider the staff at the London and New York airports.
[src:text-generation-inference/latency-engineering] Only a limited number of planes are able to make the transatlantic journey, so when one lands, they must prepare it for the return trip as quickly as possible.
[src:text-generation-inference/latency-engineering] However, cleaning, refueling and loading the cargo can be done at the same time.
[src:text-generation-inference/latency-engineering] Passengers can only be loaded after cleaning is complete.
[src:text-generation-inference/latency-engineering] The people involved in the turnaround are interested only in the time it takes for their individual tasks.
[src:text-generation-inference/latency-engineering] When all of the tasks are done at the same time, however, it is possible to reduce the latency to the length of the longest task.
[src:text-generation-inference/latency-engineering] If some steps have prerequisites, it becomes more difficult to perform all steps in parallel.
[src:text-generation-inference/latency-engineering] In the example above, the requirement to clean the plane before loading passengers results in a minimum latency longer than any single task.
[src:text-generation-inference/latency-engineering] Any mechanical process encounters limitations modeled by Newtonian physics.
[src:text-generation-inference/latency-engineering] The behavior of disk drives provides an example of mechanical latency.
[src:text-generation-inference/latency-engineering] Here, it is the time seek time for the actuator arm to be positioned above the appropriate track and then rotational latency for the data encoded on a platter to rotate from its current position to a position under the disk read-and-write head.
[src:text-generation-inference/latency-engineering] Computers run instructions in the context of a process.
[src:text-generation-inference/latency-engineering] In the context of computer multitasking, the execution of the process can be postponed if other processes are also executing.
[src:text-generation-inference/latency-engineering] In addition, the operating system can schedule when to perform the action that the process is commanding.
[src:text-generation-inference/latency-engineering] For example, suppose a process commands that a computer card's voltage output be set high-low-high-low and so on at a rate of 1000 Hz.
[src:text-generation-inference/latency-engineering] The operating system schedules the process for each transition (high-low or low-high) based on a hardware clock, such as the High Precision Event Timer.
[src:text-generation-inference/latency-engineering] The latency is the delay between the events generated by the hardware clock and the actual transitions of voltage from high to low or low to high.
[src:text-generation-inference/latency-engineering] Many desktop operating systems have performance limitations that create additional latency.
[src:text-generation-inference/latency-engineering] The problem may be mitigated with real-time extensions and patches such as PREEMPT RT.
[src:text-generation-inference/latency-engineering] On embedded systems, the real-time execution of instructions is often supported by a real-time operating system.
[src:text-generation-inference/latency-engineering] Note that in software systems, benchmarking against *average* and *median* latency can be misleading because a few outliers can distort them.
[src:text-generation-inference/latency-engineering] Instead, software architects and software developers should use "99th percentile".
[src:text-generation-inference/latency-engineering] In simulation applications, latency refers to the time delay, often measured in milliseconds, between initial input and output clearly discernible to the simulator trainee or simulator subject.
[src:text-generation-inference/latency-engineering] Latency is sometimes also called *transport delay*.
[src:text-generation-inference/latency-engineering] Some authorities distinguish between latency and transport delay by using the term *latency* in the sense of the extra time delay of a system over and above the reaction time of the vehicle being simulated, but this requires detailed knowledge of the vehicle dynamics and can be controversial.
[src:text-generation-inference/latency-engineering] In simulators with both visual and motion systems, it is particularly important that the latency of the motion system not be greater than of the visual system, or symptoms of simulator sickness may result.
[src:text-generation-inference/latency-engineering] This is because, in the real world, motion cues are those of acceleration and are quickly transmitted to the brain, typically in less than 50 milliseconds; this is followed some milliseconds later by a perception of change in the visual scene.
[src:text-generation-inference/latency-engineering] The visual scene change is essentially one of change of perspective or displacement of objects, such as the horizon, which takes some time to build up to discernible amounts after the initial acceleration that caused the displacement.
[src:text-generation-inference/latency-engineering] A simulator should, therefore, reflect the real-world situation by ensuring that the motion latency is equal to or less than that of the visual system and not the other way round.
[src:text-generation-inference/natural-language-generation] While it is widely agreed that the output of any NLG process is text, there is some disagreement about whether the inputs of an NLG system need to be non-linguistic.
[src:text-generation-inference/natural-language-generation] Common applications of NLG methods include the production of various reports, for example weather and patient reports; image captions; and chatbots like ChatGPT.
[src:text-generation-inference/natural-language-generation] Automated NLG can be compared to the process humans use when they turn ideas into writing or speech.
[src:text-generation-inference/natural-language-generation] Psycholinguists prefer the term language production for this process, which can also be described in mathematical terms, or modeled in a computer for psychological research.
[src:text-generation-inference/natural-language-generation] NLG systems can also be compared to translators of artificial computer languages, such as decompilers or transpilers, which also produce human-readable code generated from an intermediate representation.
[src:text-generation-inference/natural-language-generation] Human languages tend to be considerably more complex and allow for much more ambiguity and variety of expression than programming languages, which makes NLG more challenging.
[src:text-generation-inference/natural-language-generation] The practical considerations in building NLU vs.
[src:text-generation-inference/natural-language-generation] NLU needs to deal with ambiguous or erroneous user input, whereas the ideas the system wants to express through NLG are generally known precisely.
[src:text-generation-inference/natural-language-generation] NLG needs to choose a specific, self-consistent textual representation from many potential representations, whereas NLU generally tries to produce a single, normalized representation of the idea expressed.
[src:text-generation-inference/natural-language-generation] NLG has existed since ELIZA was developed in the mid 1960s, but the methods were first used commercially in the 1990s.
[src:text-generation-inference/natural-language-generation] NLG techniques range from simple template-based systems like a mail merge that generates form letters, to systems that have a complex understanding of human grammar.
[src:text-generation-inference/natural-language-generation] NLG can also be accomplished by training a statistical model using machine learning, typically on a large corpus of human-written texts.
[src:text-generation-inference/natural-language-generation] The *Pollen Forecast for Scotland* system is a simple example of a simple NLG system that could essentially be based on a template.
[src:text-generation-inference/natural-language-generation] This system takes as input six numbers, which give predicted pollen levels in different parts of Scotland.
[src:text-generation-inference/natural-language-generation] From these numbers, the system generates a short textual summary of pollen levels as its output.
[src:text-generation-inference/natural-language-generation] Comparing these two illustrates some of the choices that NLG systems must make; these are further discussed below.
[src:text-generation-inference/natural-language-generation] The process to generate text can be as simple as keeping a list of canned text that is copied and pasted, possibly linked with some glue text.
[src:text-generation-inference/natural-language-generation] The results may be satisfactory in simple domains such as horoscope machines or generators of personalized business letters.
[src:text-generation-inference/natural-language-generation] However, a sophisticated NLG system needs to include stages of planning and merging of information to enable the generation of text that looks natural and does not become repetitive.
[src:text-generation-inference/natural-language-generation] Deciding what information to mention in the text.
[src:text-generation-inference/natural-language-generation] For instance, in the pollen example above, deciding whether to explicitly mention that pollen level is 7 in the southeast.
[src:text-generation-inference/natural-language-generation] Overall organisation of the information to convey.
[src:text-generation-inference/natural-language-generation] For example, deciding to describe the areas with high pollen levels first, instead of the areas with low pollen levels.
[src:text-generation-inference/natural-language-generation] Merging of similar sentences to improve readability and naturalness.
[src:text-generation-inference/natural-language-generation] should be used when describing a pollen level of 4.
[src:text-generation-inference/natural-language-generation] to refer to a certain region in Scotland.
[src:text-generation-inference/natural-language-generation] An alternative approach to NLG is to use "end-to-end" machine learning to build a system, without having separate stages as above.
[src:text-generation-inference/natural-language-generation] In other words, we build an NLG system by training a machine learning algorithm (often an LSTM) on a large data set of input data and corresponding (human-written) output texts.
[src:text-generation-inference/natural-language-generation] The end-to-end approach has perhaps been most successful in image captioning, that is automatically generating a textual caption for an image.
[src:text-generation-inference/natural-language-generation] From a commercial perspective, the most successful NLG applications have been *data-to-text* systems which generate textual summaries of databases and data sets; these systems usually perform data analysis as well as text generation.
[src:text-generation-inference/natural-language-generation] Research has shown that textual summaries can be more effective than graphs and other visuals for decision support, and that computer-generated texts can be superior (from the reader's perspective) to human-written texts.
[src:text-generation-inference/natural-language-generation] The first commercial data-to-text systems produced weather forecasts from weather data.
[src:text-generation-inference/natural-language-generation] The earliest such system to be deployed was FoG, which was used by Environment Canada to generate weather forecasts in French and English in the early 1990s.
[src:text-generation-inference/natural-language-generation] The success of FoG triggered other work, both research and commercial.
[src:text-generation-inference/natural-language-generation] Recent applications include the UK Met Office's text-enhanced forecast.
[src:text-generation-inference/natural-language-generation] Data-to-text systems have since been applied in a range of settings.
[src:text-generation-inference/natural-language-generation] Following the minor earthquake near Beverly Hills, California on March 17, 2014, The Los Angeles Times reported details about the time, location and strength of the quake within 3 minutes of the event.
[src:text-generation-inference/natural-language-generation] This report was automatically generated by a 'robo-journalist', which converted the incoming data into text via a preset template.
[src:text-generation-inference/natural-language-generation] Currently there is considerable commercial interest in using NLG to summarise financial and business data.
[src:text-generation-inference/natural-language-generation] Indeed, Gartner has said that NLG will become a standard feature of 90% of modern BI and analytics platforms.
[src:text-generation-inference/natural-language-generation] NLG is also being used commercially in automated journalism, chatbots, generating product descriptions for e-commerce sites, summarising medical records, and enhancing accessibility (for example by describing graphs and data sets to blind people).
[src:text-generation-inference/natural-language-generation] An example of an interactive use of NLG is the WYSIWYM framework.
[src:text-generation-inference/natural-language-generation] It stands for *What you see is what you meant* and allows users to see and manipulate the continuously rendered view (NLG output) of an underlying formal language document (NLG input), thereby editing the formal language without learning it.
[src:text-generation-inference/natural-language-generation] Looking ahead, the current progress in data-to-text generation paves the way for tailoring texts to specific audiences.
[src:text-generation-inference/natural-language-generation] For example, data from babies in neonatal care can be converted into text differently in a clinical setting, with different levels of technical detail and explanatory language, depending on intended recipient of the text (doctor, nurse, patient).
[src:text-generation-inference/natural-language-generation] The same idea can be applied in a sports setting, with different reports generated for fans of specific teams.
[src:text-generation-inference/natural-language-generation] Over the past few years, there has been an increased interest in automatically generating captions for images, as part of a broader endeavor to investigate the interface between vision and language.
[src:text-generation-inference/natural-language-generation] A case of data-to-text generation, the algorithm of image captioning (or automatic image description) involves taking an image, analyzing its visual content, and generating a textual description (typically a sentence) that verbalizes the most prominent aspects of the image.
[src:text-generation-inference/natural-language-generation] An image captioning system involves two sub-tasks.
[src:text-generation-inference/natural-language-generation] In Image Analysis, features and attributes of an image are detected and labelled, before mapping these outputs to linguistic structures.
[src:text-generation-inference/natural-language-generation] Recent research utilize*s* deep learning approaches through features from a pre-trained convolutional neural network such as AlexNet, VGG or Caffe, where caption generators use an activation layer from the pre-trained network as their input features.
[src:text-generation-inference/natural-language-generation] Text Generation, the second task, is performed using a wide range of techniques.
[src:text-generation-inference/natural-language-generation] For example, in the Midge system, input images are represented as triples consisting of object/stuff detections, action/pose detections and spatial relations.
[src:text-generation-inference/natural-language-generation] These are subsequently mapped to <noun, verb, preposition> triples and realized using a tree substitution grammar.
[src:text-generation-inference/natural-language-generation] A common method in image captioning is to use a vision model (such as a ResNet) to encode an image into a vector, then use a language model (such as an RNN) to decode the vector into a caption.
[src:text-generation-inference/natural-language-generation] Despite advancements, challenges and opportunities remain in image capturing research.
[src:text-generation-inference/natural-language-generation] Other open challenges include visual question-answering (VQA), as well as the construction and evaluation multilingual repositories for image description.
[src:text-generation-inference/natural-language-generation] Another area where NLG has been widely applied is automated dialogue systems, frequently in the form of chatbots.
[src:text-generation-inference/natural-language-generation] A chatbot or chatterbot is a software application used to conduct an on-line chat conversation via text or text-to-speech, in lieu of providing direct contact with a live human agent.
[src:text-generation-inference/natural-language-generation] While natural language processing (NLP) techniques are applied in deciphering human input, NLG informs the output part of the chatbot algorithms in facilitating real-time dialogues.
[src:text-generation-inference/natural-language-generation] Early chatbot systems, including Cleverbot created by Rollo Carpenter in 1988 and published in 1997, reply to questions by identifying how a human has responded to the same question in a conversation database using information retrieval (IR) techniques.
[src:text-generation-inference/natural-language-generation] Modern chatbot systems predominantly rely on machine learning (ML) models, such as sequence-to-sequence learning and reinforcement learning to generate natural language output.
[src:text-generation-inference/natural-language-generation] For example, the Alibaba shopping assistant first uses an IR approach to retrieve the best candidates from the knowledge base, then uses the ML-driven seq2seq model re-rank the candidate responses and generate the answer.
[src:text-generation-inference/natural-language-generation] Creative language generation by NLG has been hypothesized since the field's origins.
[src:text-generation-inference/natural-language-generation] A recent pioneer in the area is Phillip Parker, who has developed an arsenal of algorithms capable of automatically generating textbooks, crossword puzzles, poems and books on topics ranging from bookbinding to cataracts.
[src:text-generation-inference/natural-language-generation] The advent of large pretrained transformer-based language models such as GPT-3 has also enabled breakthroughs, with such models demonstrating recognizable ability for creating-writing tasks.
[src:text-generation-inference/natural-language-generation] A related area of NLG application is computational humor production.
[src:text-generation-inference/natural-language-generation] JAPE (Joke Analysis and Production Engine) is one of the earliest large, automated humor production systems that uses a hand-coded template-based approach to create punning riddles for children.
[src:text-generation-inference/natural-language-generation] HAHAcronym creates humorous reinterpretations of any given acronym, as well as proposing new fitting acronyms given some keywords.
[src:text-generation-inference/natural-language-generation] Despite progresses, many challenges remain in producing automated creative and humorous content that rival human output.
[src:text-generation-inference/natural-language-generation] In an experiment for generating satirical headlines, outputs of their best BERT-based model were perceived as funny 9.4% of the time (while real headlines from *The Onion* were 38.4%) and a GPT-2 model fine-tuned on satirical headlines achieved 6.9%.
[src:text-generation-inference/natural-language-generation] It has been pointed out that two main issues with humor-generation systems are the lack of annotated data sets and the lack of formal evaluation methods, which could be applicable to other creative content generation.
[src:text-generation-inference/natural-language-generation] Some have argued relative to other applications, there has been a lack of attention to creative aspects of language production within NLG.
[src:text-generation-inference/natural-language-generation] NLG researchers stand to benefit from insights into what constitutes creative language production, as well as structural features of narrative that have the potential to improve NLG output even in data-to-text systems.
[src:text-generation-inference/natural-language-generation] As in other scientific fields, NLG researchers need to test how well their systems, modules, and algorithms work.
[src:text-generation-inference/natural-language-generation] An ultimate goal is how useful NLG systems are at helping people, which is the first of the above techniques.
[src:text-generation-inference/natural-language-generation] However, task-based evaluations are time-consuming and expensive, and can be difficult to carry out (especially if they require subjects with specialised expertise, such as doctors).
[src:text-generation-inference/natural-language-generation] Hence (as in other areas of NLP) task-based evaluations are the exception, not the norm.
[src:text-generation-inference/natural-language-generation] Recently researchers are assessing how well human-ratings and metrics correlate with (predict) task-based evaluations.
[src:text-generation-inference/natural-language-generation] Work is being conducted in the context of Generation Challenges shared-task events.
[src:text-generation-inference/natural-language-generation] Initial results suggest that human ratings are much better than metrics in this regard.
[src:text-generation-inference/natural-language-generation] In other words, human ratings usually do predict task-effectiveness at least to some degree (although there are exceptions), while ratings produced by metrics often do not predict task-effectiveness well.
[src:text-generation-inference/natural-language-generation] In any case, human ratings are the most popular evaluation technique in NLG; this is contrast to machine translation, where metrics are widely used.
[src:text-generation-inference/natural-language-generation] An AI can be graded on *faithfulness* to its training data or, alternatively, on *factuality*.
[src:text-generation-inference/natural-language-generation] A response that reflects the training data but not reality is faithful but not factual.
[src:text-generation-inference/natural-language-generation] A confident but unfaithful response is a *hallucination*.
[src:text-generation-inference/natural-language-generation] In Natural Language Processing, a hallucination is often defined as "generated content that is nonsensical or unfaithful to the provided source content".
[src:text-generation-inference/throughput] The **aggregate throughput** is the sum of the data rates that are delivered over all channels in a network.
[src:text-generation-inference/throughput] Throughput represents digital bandwidth consumption.
[src:text-generation-inference/throughput] The throughput of a communication system may be affected by various factors, including the limitations of the underlying physical medium, available processing power of the system components, end-user behavior, etc.
[src:text-generation-inference/throughput] When taking various protocol overheads into account, the useful rate of the data transfer can be significantly lower than the maximum achievable throughput; the useful part is usually referred to as goodput.
[src:text-generation-inference/throughput] Users of telecommunications devices, systems designers, and researchers into communication theory are often interested in knowing the expected performance of a system.
[src:text-generation-inference/throughput] From a user perspective, this is often phrased as either "which device will get my data there most effectively for my needs?", or "which device will deliver the most data per unit cost?".
[src:text-generation-inference/throughput] Systems designers often select the most effective architecture or design constraints for a system, which drive its final performance.
[src:text-generation-inference/throughput] In most cases, the benchmark of what a system is capable of, or its *maximum performance* is what the user or designer is interested in.
[src:text-generation-inference/throughput] The term *maximum throughput* is frequently used when discussing end-user maximum throughput tests.
[src:text-generation-inference/throughput] Maximum throughput is essentially synonymous with digital bandwidth capacity.
[src:text-generation-inference/throughput] Four different values are relevant in the context of maximum throughput are used in comparing the *upper limit* conceptual performance of multiple systems.
[src:text-generation-inference/throughput] They are *maximum theoretical throughput*, *maximum achievable throughput*, *peak measured throughput*, and *maximum sustained throughput*.
[src:text-generation-inference/throughput] These values represent different qualities, and care must be taken that the same definitions are used when comparing different *maximum throughput* values.
[src:text-generation-inference/throughput] Each bit must carry the same amount of information if throughput values are to be compared.
[src:text-generation-inference/throughput] Data compression can significantly alter throughput calculations, including generating values exceeding 100% in some cases.
[src:text-generation-inference/throughput] If the communication is mediated by several links in series with different bit rates, the maximum throughput of the overall link is lower than or equal to the lowest bit rate.
[src:text-generation-inference/throughput] The lowest value link in the series is referred to as the bottleneck.
[src:text-generation-inference/throughput] Maximum theoretical throughput is closely related to the channel capacity of the system, and is the maximum possible quantity of data that can be transmitted under ideal circumstances.
[src:text-generation-inference/throughput] In some cases, this number is reported as equal to the channel capacity, though this can be deceptive, as only non-packetized systems technologies can achieve this.
[src:text-generation-inference/throughput] Maximum theoretical throughput is more accurately reported taking into account format and specification overhead with best-case assumptions.
[src:text-generation-inference/throughput] The **asymptotic throughput** (less formal **asymptotic bandwidth**) for a packet-mode communication network is the value of the maximum throughput function, when the incoming network load approaches infinity, either due to a message size, or the number of data sources.
[src:text-generation-inference/throughput] As with other bit rates and data bandwidths, the asymptotic throughput is measured in bits per second (bit/s) or (rarely) bytes per second (B/s), where 1 B/s is 8 bit/s.
[src:text-generation-inference/throughput] Decimal prefixes are used, meaning that 1 Mbit/s is 1000000 bit/s.
[src:text-generation-inference/throughput] Asymptotic throughput is usually estimated by sending or simulating a very large message (sequence of data packets) through the network, using a greedy source and no flow control mechanism (i.e., UDP rather than TCP), and measuring the volume of data received at the destination node.
[src:text-generation-inference/throughput] Traffic load between other sources may reduce this maximum network path throughput.
[src:text-generation-inference/throughput] Alternatively, a large number of sources and sinks may be modeled, with or without flow control, and the aggregate maximum network throughput measured (the sum of traffic reaching its destinations).
[src:text-generation-inference/throughput] A well-known application of asymptotic throughput is in modeling point-to-point communication where message latency $T(N)$ is modeled as a function of message length N as $T(N)=(M+N)/A$ where A is the asymptotic bandwidth and M is the half-peak length.
[src:text-generation-inference/throughput] As well as its use in general network modeling, asymptotic throughput is used in modeling performance on massively parallel computer systems, where system operation is highly dependent on communication overhead, as well as processor performance.
[src:text-generation-inference/throughput] In these applications, asymptotic throughput is used modeling which includes the number of processors, so that both the latency and the asymptotic throughput are functions of the number of processors.
[src:text-generation-inference/throughput] Where asymptotic throughput is a theoretical or calculated capacity, *peak measured throughput* is throughput measured on a real implemented system, or on a simulated system.
[src:text-generation-inference/throughput] The value is the throughput measured over a short period of time; mathematically, this is the limit taken with respect to throughput as time approaches zero.
[src:text-generation-inference/throughput] This term is synonymous with *instantaneous throughput*.
[src:text-generation-inference/throughput] This number is useful for systems that rely on burst data transmission; however, for systems with a high duty cycle, this is less likely to be a useful measure of system performance.
[src:text-generation-inference/throughput] Maximum sustained throughput is the throughput averaged or integrated over a long time.
[src:text-generation-inference/throughput] For networks under constant load, this is likely to be the most accurate indicator of system performance.
[src:text-generation-inference/throughput] The maximum throughput is defined as the asymptotic throughput when the load is large.
[src:text-generation-inference/throughput] In packet-switched networks while packet loss is not occurring, the load and the throughput always are equal.
[src:text-generation-inference/throughput] The maximum throughput may be defined as the minimum load in bit/s that causes packet loss or causes the latency to become unstable and increase towards infinity.
[src:text-generation-inference/throughput] Throughput is sometimes normalized and measured in percentage, but normalization may cause confusion regarding what the percentage is related to.
[src:text-generation-inference/throughput] *Channel utilization*, *channel efficiency* and *packet drop rate* in percentage are less ambiguous terms.
[src:text-generation-inference/throughput] The channel efficiency, also known as bandwidth utilization efficiency, is the percentage of the net bit rate (in bit/s) of a digital communication channel that goes to the achieved throughput.
[src:text-generation-inference/throughput] For example, if the throughput is 70 Mbit/s over a 100 Mbit/s Ethernet connection, the channel efficiency is 70%.
[src:text-generation-inference/throughput] Channel utilization includes both the data bits and the transmission overhead in the channel.
[src:text-generation-inference/throughput] The transmission overhead consists of preamble sequences, frame headers and acknowledgment packets.
[src:text-generation-inference/throughput] In a simplistic approach, channel efficiency can be equal to channel utilization assuming that acknowledge packets are zero-length and that the communications provider will not see any bandwidth relative to retransmissions or headers.
[src:text-generation-inference/throughput] Therefore, certain texts mark a difference between channel utilization and protocol efficiency.
[src:text-generation-inference/throughput] For example, the maximum frame size in Ethernet is 1526 bytes: up to 1500 bytes for the payload, eight bytes for the preamble, 14 bytes for the header, and 4 bytes for the trailer.
[src:text-generation-inference/throughput] An additional minimum interframe gap corresponding to 12 bytes is inserted after each frame.
[src:text-generation-inference/throughput] This corresponds to a maximum channel utilization of 1526 / (1526 + 12) × 100% = 99.22%, or a maximum channel use of 99.22 Mbit/s inclusive of Ethernet datalink layer protocol overhead over a 100 Mbit/s Ethernet connection.
[src:text-generation-inference/throughput] The maximum throughput or channel efficiency is then 1500 / (1526 + 12) = 97.5%, exclusive of the Ethernet protocol overhead.
[src:text-generation-inference/throughput] The throughput of a communication system will be limited by a number of factors.
[src:text-generation-inference/throughput] The maximum achievable throughput (the channel capacity) is affected by the bandwidth in hertz and signal-to-noise ratio of the analog physical medium.
[src:text-generation-inference/throughput] Limited current drive capability in communications equipment can limit the effective signal-to-noise ratio for high capacitance links.
[src:text-generation-inference/throughput] Despite the conceptual simplicity of digital information, all electrical signals traveling over wires are analog.
[src:text-generation-inference/throughput] The analog limitations of wires or wireless systems inevitably provide an upper bound on the amount of information that can be sent.
[src:text-generation-inference/throughput] The dominant equation here is the Shannon–Hartley theorem, and analog limitations of this type can be understood as factors that affect either the analog bandwidth of a signal or as factors that affect the signal-to-noise ratio.
[src:text-generation-inference/throughput] The bandwidth of twisted pair cabling used by Ethernet is limited to approximately 1 GHz, and PCB traces are limited by a similar amount.
[src:text-generation-inference/throughput] Digital systems refer to the *knee frequency*, the amount of time for the digital voltage to rise from 10% of a nominal digital 0 to a nominal digital 1 or vice versa.
[src:text-generation-inference/throughput] Large data loads that require processing impose data processing requirements on hardware.
[src:text-generation-inference/throughput] For example, a gateway router must examine and perform routing table lookups on billions of packets per second.
[src:text-generation-inference/throughput] CSMA/CD and CSMA/CA backoff waiting time and frame retransmissions after detected collisions slows transmissions.
[src:text-generation-inference/throughput] This may occur in Ethernet bus networks and hub networks, as well as in wireless networks.
[src:text-generation-inference/throughput] Flow control, for example, in the Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) protocol, affects the throughput if the bandwidth-delay product is larger than the TCP window.
[src:text-generation-inference/throughput] In that case, the sending computer must wait for acknowledgement of the data packets before it can send more packets.
[src:text-generation-inference/throughput] TCP congestion avoidance controls the data rate.
[src:text-generation-inference/throughput] A so-called *slow start* occurs in the beginning of a file transfer, and after packet drops caused by router congestion or bit errors in, for example, wireless links.
[src:text-generation-inference/throughput] Ensuring that multiple users can harmoniously share a single communications link requires some kind of equitable sharing of the link.
[src:text-generation-inference/throughput] If a communication link offering data rate *R* is shared by *N* active users, ideally, every user can typically achieve a throughput of approximately *R/N*.
[src:text-generation-inference/throughput] Network schedulers in routers and switches ultimately determine how bandwidth is shared.
[src:text-generation-inference/throughput] If fair queuing is not provided, users that send large packets will get higher bandwidth.
[src:text-generation-inference/throughput] Some users may be prioritized in a weighted fair queuing (WFQ) algorithm if differentiated or guaranteed quality of service (QoS) is provided.
[src:text-generation-inference/throughput] In some communications systems, such as satellite networks, only a finite number of channels may be available to a given user at a given time.
[src:text-generation-inference/throughput] Channels are assigned either through preassignment or through Demand Assigned Multiple Access (DAMA).
[src:text-generation-inference/throughput] In these cases, throughput is quantized per channel, and unused capacity on partially utilized channels is lost.
[src:text-generation-inference/throughput] The maximum throughput is often an unreliable measurement of effective bandwidth, for example the file transmission data rate in bits per seconds.
[src:text-generation-inference/throughput] The achieved throughput is often lower than the maximum throughput.
[src:text-generation-inference/throughput] Protocol overhead affects the effective bandwidth.
[src:text-generation-inference/throughput] In schemes that include forward error correction codes, the redundant error code is normally excluded from the throughput.
[src:text-generation-inference/throughput] An example in modem communication, where the throughput is typically measured in the interface between the Point-to-Point Protocol (PPP) and the circuit-switched modem connection.
[src:text-generation-inference/throughput] In this case, the maximum throughput is often called net bit rate or useful bit rate.
[src:text-generation-inference/throughput] To determine the actual data rate of a network or connection, the goodput measurement definition may be used.
[src:text-generation-inference/throughput] For example, in file transmission, the goodput corresponds to the file size (in bits) divided by the file transmission time.
[src:text-generation-inference/throughput] The goodput is the amount of useful information that is delivered per second to the application layer protocol.
[src:text-generation-inference/throughput] Dropped packets or packet retransmissions, as well as protocol overhead, are excluded.
[src:text-generation-inference/throughput] Because of that, the goodput is lower than the maximum throughput.
[src:text-generation-inference/throughput] Often, a block in a data flow diagram has a single input and a single output, and operates on discrete packets of information.
[src:text-generation-inference/throughput] Examples of such blocks are fast Fourier transform modules or binary multipliers.
[src:text-generation-inference/throughput] Because the units of throughput (e.g., messages per second) are the reciprocal of the unit for propagation delay (e.g., seconds per message), throughput can be used to relate a computational block to a communications channel, simplifying system analysis.
[src:text-generation-inference/throughput] In wireless networks or cellular systems, the system spectral efficiency in bit/s/Hz/area, bit/s/Hz/site or bit/s/Hz/cell units, is the maximum aggregate throughput divided by the analog bandwidth and some measure of the system coverage area.
[src:text-generation-inference/throughput] Throughput over analog channels is determined by the modulation scheme, the signal-to-noise ratio, and the available bandwidth.
[src:text-generation-inference/throughput] Since throughput is normally defined in terms of quantified digital data, the term *throughput* is not normally used; the term *bandwidth* is more often used instead.
